'''Oka Shrine''' (乎加神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Higashiomi|ja|東近江市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Shiga Prefecture, Japan. It is a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}}, previously Ranked as a Ken-sha (Prefectural Shrine). The shrine enshrines {{ill|Toyouke no Mikoto|ja|トヨウケビメ|12=draft|12=draft}} as the main deity, along with {{ill|Hakusan Hime no Mikoto|ja|菊理媛神|12=draft|12=draft}} as an associate deity.

== Overview ==
The shrine venerates {{ill|Toyouke no Mikoto|ja|トヨウケビメ|12=draft|12=draft}}, a deity worshipped for bestowing the origins of grains, silkworms, and hemp to humanity, as well as {{ill|Hakusan Hime no Mikoto|ja|菊理媛神|12=draft|12=draft}}. Listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft|12=draft}} as one of the two shrines in {{ill|Kōzuke District, Ōmi Province|ja|神崎郡|12=draft|12=draft}} (the other being {{ill|Kaketa Mikawa Shrine|ja|河桁御河邊神社|12=draft|12=draft}}), Oka Shrine is said to have been established on the imperial decree of Emperor Ingyō. According to the shrine's records, the area names such as "Kōzuke District," "Jingo," and the ancient village name "Kannushi" derive from the shrine.

[[File:Oka_jinja_information.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Historical Signage of Oka Shrine]]

North of the main hall is the {{ill|Jingo Kamezuka Kofun|ja|神郷亀塚古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, a {{ill|Late Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|12=draft|12=draft}} Kofun, which is believed to have been a ritual site in ancient times.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* {{ill|Toyouke no Mikoto|ja|トヨウケビメ|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Associate deity: {{ill|Hakusan Hime no Mikoto|ja|菊理媛神|12=draft|12=draft}}

== Grounds ==
[[File:Oka_jinja.jpg|thumb|250px|Oka Shrine Heiden]]
In 2003, the main hall<ref name="honden">[https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/101/00003249 Agency for Cultural Affairs: Database of National Cultural Properties]</ref>, haiden<ref>[https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/101/00003253 Agency for Cultural Affairs: Database of National Cultural Properties]</ref>, heiden<ref>[https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/101/00003253 Agency for Cultural Affairs: Database of National Cultural Properties]</ref>, norito-den<ref name="#1">[https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/101/00003251 Agency for Cultural Affairs: Database of National Cultural Properties]</ref>, temizuya<ref name="#1"/> and tamagaki<ref>[https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/101/00003252 Agency for Cultural Affairs: Database of National Cultural Properties]</ref> were registered as {{ill|Registered Tangible Cultural Properties (Japan)|ja|登録有形文化財|12=draft|12=draft}}. These structures, built during the Meiji era, include:
* '''Main Hall''': Shinmei-zukuri, width 3 ken, depth 2 ken. Originally part of the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} transferred in 1892 (Meiji 25).
* '''Haiden''': Hip-and-gable roof with open walls and floorless construction.
* '''Shrine Precincts''': Housing auxiliary shrines like Hiyoshi Shrine, Wakamiya Shrine, Gosha Shrine, Yasaka Shrine, and Wakamiya Shrine.

== Festivals ==
* Closest Sunday to April 9.

== Access ==
* A 20-minute walk from {{ill|Notogawa Station|ja|能登川駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Biwako Line|ja|琵琶湖線|12=draft|12=draft}}.

